title.native: バカとテストと召喚獣
title.english: Baka and Test - Summon the Beasts

entries.notes:
Lapis Re:LIGHTs starts as a simple idol show albeit coming from an unusual "magical fantasy in another world" angle. It quickly gets ambitious as the girls from the really big cast starts to appear one after another. This doesn't prevent the series of setting their personalities to a bare minimum.

The show keeps going in an episodic format where each girl group is given their one chance at development, then ends up with an idol concert. It's just a little bit after half that the main cast's group starts being the focus. A surprisingly good hook is thrown and the first (and last) real conflict of the series starts to unfold. This goes on to become an educated attempt at exploring the otherwise underused world fantasy setting and giving the series some tangible seriousness. Lapis Re:LIGHTs finishes up in the green  but the ending falters a bit both in climax and closure, the latter being like that for what I guess is the hope for a sequel.

entries.notes:
Although Moriarty the Patriot is but another japanese attempt at a Sherlock Holmes story, it does respects canon to some level.

The narrative slithers unevenly through the plot with its characters, with a late arrival of Holmes, who gets to be our PoV for some later episodes, so he could be finally set as the series antagonist. While these episodes are entertaining, they are mostly void of the original society strangling that the series was built upon. Which means this cour unfortunately ends in a note that doesn't really dialogues with its beginning.

The personal drama has little time to be developed yet still somewhat works. Besides taking time, the nonsensical interactions throughout the series sheds some light upon moments that might have been better if left darker, all the while being responsible for most of the characters' charisma.

title.native: ストライクウィッチーズ

entries.notes:
Strike Witches deals in, from beginning to end, a simple and efficient plot that doesn't grab the spectator's attention from what was supposed to be showcased: its setting and main cast. This "little to no risks" approach lets the anime shine refreshingly in an industry that got popular because of its unmeasured risk taking.

Its military aspects, mainly the structure and order, are basic yet convincing, another thing that sets this series apart from peers of the same genre.

The main cast character's development while not really fresh, is tender and sometimes elegantly hits a grace spot.
